# Drag to Reorganize — Feature Definition

> Feature addendum to `mnemo.prd` (core product + position model) and
> `locations.prd` (the visual finder this builds on). Read those first.

## Problem

Today the Locations page is **read-only** (an explicit non-goal in `locations.prd`:
"no drag-and-drop reorganization"). To move a container you leave the spatial view,
open the container's edit page, and re-assign a slot by code/address — exactly the
abstract, code-decoding chore the finder was built to kill. The wall is rendered as it
physically looks, the user is standing in front of it on a phone, and yet the one thing
they can't do is *rearrange it by touch the way they'd move a real drawer*.

Reorganizing is a real, frequent action: you free up a drawer, consolidate two
half-full ones, or pull a container off the wall to take to the bench. Each of those is
a position change the data model already supports — it just has no spatial gesture.

## Goal

From the Wall tab, let the user reorganize by **dragging a drawer**:

- **Drag onto another drawer in the same cabinet → swap.** The two containers exchange
  slots in place. Drag onto an **empty** drawer and it simply moves there.
- **Drag onto the bench → bench.** The container leaves the wall (position cleared) and
  lands in the **bench**, a globally-available list of un-placed containers.
- **The bench is the bridge for everything else.** You can only see one cabinet's drawers
  at a time, so moving a container to a *different* cabinet goes through the bench: drag
  it off, switch cabinets, drag it back out of the bench onto a drawer. To make that
  workable, the bench is reachable from **every page** as a collapsible sidebar.

One gesture, done in front of the physical wall, with the on-screen layout updating to
match what you just did with your hands. This lifts the read-only restriction for
**container positions only** — it does not touch fixtures (that's `layout-editor.prd`).

## Non-Goals (this iteration)

- **Editing fixtures by drag.** Cabinets, chests, slots, and wall placement are not
  draggable here — that's `layout-editor.prd`. This feature moves *containers between
  existing slots*, nothing else.
- **The Part/Container/nesting model.** Containers, parts, the 2-level nesting cap, and
  the position invariant are unchanged. A drag resolves to exactly the existing
  `assign-slot` / `bench` operations (plus one new *swap*); no new position types.
- **Tackle / Printer tabs.** Drag lives on the **Wall** tab first, the only built-out
  tab. The same gestures can extend to the others when they're built (see Open Q).
- **Drag-to-nest.** Dropping a container *into* another to nest it is a separate idea;
  this round is slot↔slot swap and slot→bench only.
- **Multi-select / bulk move.** One container per drag.

## Core interaction

The Wall tab's `CabinetDetail` already renders each drawer as a button cell showing its
address and occupant label. This feature makes an **occupied** cell draggable and makes
cells (and a bench target) valid **drop zones**.

Drag sources and drop outcomes:

| Drag from | Drop on | Outcome |
| --- | --- | --- |
| occupied drawer | **empty** drawer | move: source container → target slot |
| occupied drawer | **occupied** drawer (same cabinet) | **swap**: the two containers exchange slots |
| occupied drawer | **bench** (sidebar / drop zone) | bench: source container's position cleared |
| **bench chip** | empty drawer | place: benched container → target slot |
| **bench chip** | occupied drawer | swap: benched container ⇄ that drawer's occupant |
| empty drawer | anything | not draggable (nothing to move) |

- **Tap is preserved.** A short tap still does what it does today (open the occupant's
  container, or create-and-name in an empty drawer). Only a *drag* gesture reorganizes.
  Distinguishing tap from drag-start is the central interaction detail (see UX).
- **Drop is confirmed implicitly by release**, not a modal — a fast, direct-manipulation
  feel. A *swap* moves two containers at once, so the post-drop toast names both ("Swapped
  *Resistors 10k* ⇄ *Capacitors*") to make an accidental swap obvious and undoable.

### Swap vs. bump — the one non-obvious rule

The existing `assign_slot()` is **not** a swap: assigning A to an occupied slot *bumps*
the occupant B to **benched** (the documented unique-slot rule). That's correct for the
container edit flow, but it's the **wrong** outcome for a drag-onto-occupied gesture,
where the user's mental model is "trade places" — bumping B silently off the wall is a
surprise. So drag-onto-occupied needs **true swap** semantics: A takes B's slot *and* B
takes A's slot, atomically, neither benched. This is a new operation, not the existing
assign (see API).

Drag-onto-**empty** is an ordinary move and can reuse `assign_slot()` as-is (no occupant
to bump).

## The bench sidebar — bridge for cross-cabinet moves

Only one cabinet's drawers are on screen at a time (the detail view), so a *direct* drag
from cabinet 3 to cabinet 7 isn't expressible — you can't drop on a drawer you can't see.
**The bench is the required intermediary:** drag off the wall to bench, switch cabinets
via the minimap, then drag the container back out of the bench onto a drawer. So the bench
must be both a **drop target** (to bench) and a **drag source** (to place), and it must be
visible while you navigate between cabinets.

The bench therefore lives as a **collapsible sidebar available on every page**, not just a
Wall-tab tray:

- It renders in **`web/src/components/Layout.jsx`**, which already wraps every authenticated
  route, so it's present on the Locations page *and* on each container page — satisfying
  "view the bench from every container page."
- **Orientation is reactive to the viewport's aspect ratio:** wider-than-tall (landscape /
  desktop) → a **left edge drawer**; taller-than-wide (portrait phone) → a **bottom sheet**.
  It's the same component and behavior; only the docking edge and slide axis swap, chosen
  from a CSS aspect-ratio / matchMedia breakpoint so it re-docks live on rotation. This puts
  the handle on whichever edge has the room and lands the chips along the screen's long axis.
- **Defaults collapsed** to a thin edge tab/handle so it never crowds the phone layout;
  tapping the handle (or starting a drag) expands it. State (collapsed/expanded) persists
  across navigation.
- Its contents are the existing **`GET /containers/benched`** list under the existing
  **`['benched']`** query key — no new read. Each benched container is a **chip** that is a
  drag source: drag a chip onto an empty drawer to place it, or onto an occupied drawer to
  swap. A chip also links to that container's page (tap, as today).
- It **replaces the standalone `/benched` page**, which is retired: drop the route and the
  `BenchedPage` import in `App.jsx`, remove the "Benched" `NavLink` in `Layout.jsx`, and
  redirect any lingering `/benched` link to where the bench now lives (the sidebar). The
  sidebar is now the one place to see and act on benched containers.

Because the sidebar is global, "switch cabinets and place from the bench" works without any
Wall-tab-specific tray, and the same bench is the staging area for the container-edit flow
that already exists.

## UX / UX details (mobile-first is the hard part)

mnemo is phone-first, and **HTML5 drag-and-drop does not work on touch.** This is the
defining implementation constraint, not a footnote:

- Use a **pointer-events based** drag (Pointer Events API, or a touch-capable DnD lib)
  so it works identically with finger and mouse. Don't reach for native `draggable`.
- **Long-press to lift (decided).** A drag starts only after a **press-and-hold** on an
  occupied drawer; a plain tap still opens the drawer and a plain drag still scrolls the
  page. The press-and-hold is the unambiguous "now you're moving it" signal on touch
  (worth a subtle lift animation / haptic-style cue at the threshold).
- **Live feedback:** the lifted drawer follows the finger (or a ghost does); valid drop
  targets highlight; the hovered target shows what will happen (a *swap* badge over an
  occupied drawer, a *move* outline over an empty one). Reuse the existing `flash`
  highlight vocabulary where possible.
- **Scroll vs. drag:** a cabinet can be taller than the viewport; the drag must not fight
  page scroll. Long-press-to-lift resolves this — a plain drag scrolls, a held drag moves.
- **Bench as drop target:** the collapsed bench handle/edge acts as the drop zone. Lifting
  a drawer can auto-reveal (peek-open) the bench sidebar so the target is obviously there,
  then re-collapse on release.
- **Optimistic update + rollback.** Reflect the move immediately (TanStack Query optimistic
  update on `['bins']`), then reconcile with the server; on failure, snap back and toast.
- **Undo.** Because a drop is committed on release with no confirm, a brief **Undo** on the
  success toast is the safety net — especially for swaps. (Undo = the inverse op: swap back,
  or re-assign the benched container to its prior slot.)

The read-only finder stays the default; dragging is just what a press-and-hold on an
occupied drawer now affords. No separate "edit mode" toggle is needed for container moves
(unlike the fixture editor, which does gate behind a mode).

## API Requirements

The two simple outcomes already exist and are reused unchanged:

- **Move to empty slot** → `POST /containers/{id}/assign-slot` (`assign_slot()`; no
  occupant, so no bump).
- **Bench** → `POST /containers/{id}/bench`.

The **swap** needs a new, transactional operation, because doing it as two client-side
assigns would (a) bump one occupant to benched between the calls and (b) be non-atomic.
Conceptually:

- **`POST /containers/{id}/swap-slot`** with `{ slot_id }` (the *target* slot, currently
  occupied by B): in one transaction, give A the target slot and give B the source slot,
  benching neither. Lives next to `assign_slot()` in `positions.py` — it owns the unique
  slot bump and benching, and this is a sibling rule. The unique `containers.slot_id`
  constraint means the swap must stage through a `flush()` (e.g. clear both, flush, then
  set both) exactly as `assign_slot()` does to avoid tripping uniqueness mid-swap.
  - **Validate** that the source container actually holds the source slot the client
    thinks it does (guard against a stale `['bins']` cache reordering under the user).

Reads still come from `GET /bins` unchanged — a drag just re-fetches/optimistically edits
it. **No migration** is needed; this is pure position movement over the existing schema.

## Edge cases / safety

- **Stale position (the expected case from `mnemo.prd`).** Two containers may already share
  a last-known slot from an un-logged move — an *acceptable* state, not an error. A drag
  onto such a slot should still resolve sensibly (treat as occupied → swap with the chosen
  occupant); don't crash on the double-occupancy the model permits.
- **Drop on self / drop on same slot** → no-op, no server call.
- **Drag a benched chip onto its own (now empty) origin** → ordinary assign.
- **Concurrent edit** → the swap endpoint's source-slot validation rejects a move computed
  against a stale board; the client re-fetches and the user re-tries.

## Build Phasing

1. **Bench sidebar (read-only).** The collapsible, every-page bench in `Layout.jsx`,
   defaulting collapsed, rendering the existing `['benched']` list as chips. Useful on its
   own (the bench is finally visible everywhere) and the foundation for the drag target.
2. **Drag-to-bench, single cabinet.** Long-press lift on an occupied drawer → drop on the
   bench sidebar, optimistic update + undo toast. Reuses `POST .../bench`. Smallest slice
   that pulls a drawer off the wall.
3. **Drag-to-move / swap within a cabinet.** Drop on empty (reuse `assign-slot`) and drop
   on occupied (new **`swap-slot`** endpoint), with the swap toast + undo.
4. **Bench chips as a drag source.** Drag a benched chip onto a drawer to place/swap,
   completing the cross-cabinet flow (bench → switch cabinet → place).

### Decided

- **Swap is a real, new operation** — drag-onto-occupied **swaps** (neither benched), via a
  new transactional `POST /containers/{id}/swap-slot`; the existing bump-to-benched assign
  is *not* reused for occupied targets.
- **Long-press to lift** is the drag-start gesture (tap opens, plain drag scrolls).
- **The bench is the required intermediary** for cross-cabinet moves, surfaced as a
  **collapsible, every-page sidebar** (defaults collapsed) in `Layout.jsx`, whose dock is
  **reactive**: left edge when the viewport is wider than tall, bottom sheet when taller
  than wide.
- **The `/benched` page is retired** and replaced by the sidebar.

## Open Questions

- **Undo lifetime** — toast-duration undo only, or a small persistent "undo last move"?
  Swaps especially want a forgiving window.
- **Extending to Tackle/Printer tabs** — the same swap/bench gestures generalize, but those
  tabs aren't built yet (`locations.prd`). Defer until they exist, or design the drag layer
  tab-agnostically now so it drops in for free?
